                },
                {
                  "$type": "Models.Functions.MultiplyFunction, Models",
                  "Name": "PotentialBerrySizeAdj",
                  "Children": [
                    {
                      "$type": "Models.Memo, Models",
                      "Text": "\r\nTemperature or rainful during flowering to fruitset would affect the pollination. a good pollination will result in a high fertility and large seed. the size of the seeds would affect the potential size of the berry. See Adam Friend's thesis. \r\n\r\nPollination alone results in the development of small, hard green berries (live green ovaries or LGO). Further development requires fertilization of grape ovaries and subsequent seed development (Friend et al. 2009). Should ovules not fully develop, leaving seed traces,  the berries will ripen, but remain small, while successful fertilization of one or more ovule will result in complete berry development, with the berry mass generally reflecting seed mass. The success of fertilization depends on the pollen viability and environmental factors such as temperature, carbohydrate availability and vine nutrition.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(Ojeda et al. 2001) analysed the effects of water deficits after anthesis on pericarp cell division and enlargement of cv. Syrah berries. They found water deficits after anthesis did not affect cell division, but mainly limiting cell expansion. These results support the hypothesis that early water deficits modify the structural properties of the cell components and consequently cell wall extensibility, thereby limiting the subsequent enlargement of pericarp cells even with good water status after véraison. (Korkutal et al. 2011) shown water deficit with predawn water potential smaller than -0.6 MPa starting from 17 E-L stage did not affect the pollen viability and pollen germination ratios, but reduced berry set ratio, and delayed berry development.",
                      "Name": "Memo",
                      "Children": [],
                      "IncludeInDocumentation": true,
                      "Enabled": true,
                      "ReadOnly": false
                    },
                    {
                      "$type": "Models.Functions.LinearInterpolationFunction, Models",
                      "XProperty": "[Berry].MeanTempFlowering.Value()",
                      "Name": "TempFlowering",
                      "Children": [
